        <h2>. . . Lab 7 Description</h2>
        &#8195;This lab demonstrates basic usage of HTML forms.<br>
        This lab uses the POST inside of the HTML form field in order to push the given user responses to the an external <i>.php</i> website.
        This, of course has many use cases and objectives.
        For starters, this is useful as a request page.
        This page demonstrates a page where users fill out a form where appointment requests are made.<br>
        One will notice that this page also demonstrates the usage of several other commonly found form functions.
        The usage of declaring the <i>type</i> of input inside the input fields enables the usage of system-specific feilds.
        The <i>time</i> type appears differently based on operating system / web browser features.
        This can enrich the webpage without adding excess load-time / bandwidth.
      </div>
      <!-- Form - Creation and directing to https://ron.viseh.com/CIS2336/MyNotes/Chapter05/process.php -->
    <h2>Request an Appointment</h2>
    <div>
      <form action="https://ron.viseh.com/CIS2336/MyNotes/Chapter05/process.php" method="post">

        <label><i>Contact Information</i></label><br>
        <input type="text" id="name" name="name" autofocus placeholder="name"><br><br>

        <input type="text" id="email" name="email" placeholder="email*" required><br><br>
        <input type="text" id="tel-national" name="phone" placeholder="phone"><br><br>

        <label><i>Appointment Time</i></label><br>

        <input type="date" id="date" name="date"><br><br>

        <input type="time" id="time" name="time"><br><br>

        <input type="text" id="message" name="message" placeholder="message*" required><br><br>

        <input type="submit" value="Submit">
      </form>
    </div>

